  "text": "<html>\r\n    <head>\r\n    <style>\r\n        .unselectable {\r\n          -webkit-user-select: none;\r\n          -webkit-touch-callout: none;\r\n          -moz-user-select: none;\r\n          -ms-user-select: none;\r\n          user-select: none;\r\n        }\r\n      <\/style>\r\n      <\/head>\r\n\r\n<body class=\"unselectable\">\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:10pt; line-height:115%; font-size:11pt;\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">AC CIRCUIT<\/span><\/strong><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:3pt; page-break-inside:avoid; page-break-after:avoid; line-height:115%; font-size:12pt;\"><a name=\"_67rnv2l9dw27\"><\/a><strong><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">Phasors and Alternating Current<\/span><\/strong><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:10pt; line-height:115%; font-size:11pt;\"><a name=\"_wzdmhd3tk5cb\"><\/a><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">There are two kinds of current. There is the steady constant current called&nbsp;<\/span><em><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">direct current<\/span><\/em><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">&nbsp;which is the type that batteries supply. The other kind of current is called&nbsp;<\/span><strong><em><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">alternating current<\/span><\/em><\/strong><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">&nbsp;which is our main concern in this module. &quot;Alternating&quot; because it&#39;s not a steady current. By not steady, we mean it reverses back and forth, flowing in one direction and in the next minute the opposite direction.&nbsp;<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:10pt; line-height:115%; font-size:11pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">What you may not have known is that most of our devices including TV and mobile phones use alternating current than direct current. And there is a reason for that. AC current is more pliable than DC. You can step up or step-down AC but not DC. Infact, so many characteristics of AC make it inherently better than DC.<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:10pt; line-height:115%; font-size:11pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">It helps to think of DC as a constant that wouldn&#39;t change, which is actually what it is. As for AC, we can always use it to our advantage the way we want it. Hence, AC is more widely used in electronics and different kinds of circuit.&nbsp;<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:10pt; line-height:115%; font-size:11pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">Our focus in this discourse however, would be on how we can solve problems on AC circuit. It&#39;s important to understand that the same principles we apply while solving DC circuits is the same principles we need here. All you need is to follow carefully to understand how it works.<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:10pt; line-height:115%; font-size:11pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">Before we go into the problems, we will review the basic concepts that we need here.<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:10pt; line-height:115%; font-size:11pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">A sinusoidal voltage\/current might be described by the function<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:10pt; line-height:115%; font-size:11pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">v = Vcos(wt+z)-----(1)<\/span><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:10pt; line-height:115%; font-size:11pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">i = I cos(wt+z)<\/span><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">&nbsp;&nbsp;<\/span><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">-----(2)<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:10pt; line-height:115%; font-size:11pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">where v\/i is the instantaneous voltage\/current, V\/I is the maximum\/peak voltage and w is the angular frequency and z is the phase angle of the oscillating quantity.&nbsp;<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:10pt; line-height:115%; font-size:11pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">&nbsp;<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:10pt; line-height:115%; font-size:11pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">The root mean square value,&nbsp;<\/span><strong><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">rms<\/span><\/strong><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">&nbsp;of AC current is the square root of the average of the square of instantaneous current over any given cycle. It turns out we can write an expression relating this value to the peak value of current. A similar expression relates the rms voltage and the peak voltage namely:<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:10pt; line-height:115%; font-size:11pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">I<\/span><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:7.33pt;\"><sub>rms&nbsp;<\/sub><\/span><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">= I\/&radic;2-----(3)<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:10pt; line-height:115%; font-size:11pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">V<\/span><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:7.33pt;\"><sub>rms&nbsp;<\/sub><\/span><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">= V\/&radic;2---(4)<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:10pt; line-height:115%; font-size:11pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">&nbsp;<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:10pt; line-height:115%; font-size:11pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">The average power into a AC circuit is given by the general expression<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:10pt; line-height:115%; font-size:11pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">P<\/span><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:7.33pt;\"><sub>avg&nbsp;<\/sub><\/span><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">= &frac12; VI cosz = V<\/span><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:7.33pt;\"><sub>rms<\/sub><\/span><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">I<\/span><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:7.33pt;\"><sub>rms<\/sub><\/span><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">cosz-----(5)<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:10pt; line-height:115%; font-size:11pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">&nbsp;<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:10pt; line-height:115%; font-size:11pt;\"><a name=\"_ipnerragyde9\"><\/a><strong><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">AC circuit Elements<\/span><\/strong><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:10pt; line-height:115%; font-size:11pt;\"><a name=\"_63x5ay6msdwr\"><\/a><strong><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">NB<\/span><\/strong><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">: In an AC circuit that contains only a capacitor, the voltage lags behind the current by 90&deg;<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:10pt; line-height:115%; font-size:11pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">The phase relationship in a purely capacitive circuit the voltage &ldquo;LAGS&rdquo; the current by 90&deg;. But by using the voltage as our reference, we can also say that the current &ldquo;LEADS&rdquo; the voltage by one quarter of a cycle or 90&deg; as shown in the vector diagram below.<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:10pt; line-height:115%; font-size:11pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">In a Pure inductive Circuit, the current lags behind the voltage by an angle of 90 degrees. While in a Pure Resistive AC circuit, the voltage and current are in phase<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:10pt; line-height:115%; font-size:11pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">The back emf induced in a coil when a current carrying coil is mounted on a metal frame is called eddy current. They are currents induced in conductors, when the conductors are exposed to changing magnetic field due to relative motion of the field source and the conductor.<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:10pt; line-height:115%; font-size:11pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">A simple dc generator consists of a coil of wire rotating in a magnetic field. However, it uses a split ring commutator rather than the two slip rings found in alternating current (ac) generators. To convert an ac dynamo to dc dynamo, the slip rings are replaced with a split-ring commutator.<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:10pt; line-height:115%; font-size:11pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">&nbsp;<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:10pt; line-height:115%; font-size:11pt;\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">Resistor<\/span><\/strong><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:10pt; line-height:115%; font-size:11pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">The voltage and current through a resistor and in fact every circuit element in an AC circuit is given by eqns (1) and (2) as written above.&nbsp;<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:10pt; line-height:115%; font-size:11pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">Additionally, we have the relationship for the peak voltage\/current through the resistor connected to a AC circuit,<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:10pt; line-height:115%; font-size:11pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">&nbsp;<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:10pt; line-height:115%; font-size:11pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">V = IR&nbsp;<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:10pt; line-height:115%; font-size:11pt;\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">&nbsp;<\/span><\/strong><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:10pt; line-height:115%; font-size:11pt;\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">For a resistor in AC circuit, both the current and voltage are in phase with each other.&nbsp;<\/span><\/strong><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">This means that both current and voltage&nbsp;<\/span><strong><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">peak<\/span><\/strong><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">&nbsp;and&nbsp;<\/span><strong><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">zero&nbsp;<\/span><\/strong><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">together. When the ac voltage peaks, the lamp (resistor) in the circuit is brightest and vice versa.<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:10pt; line-height:115%; font-size:11pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">&nbsp;<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:10pt; line-height:115%; font-size:11pt;\"><a name=\"_nodt4gk4x50u\"><\/a><strong><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">Inductor<\/span><\/strong><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:10pt; line-height:115%; font-size:11pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">Although there is no resistance, there is a pd that appears across the inductor terminals. Since current varies with time, there is self-induced emf across the inductor terminals by Faraday&#39;s law. This induced emf is the source of voltage that appears across the inductor.<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:10pt; line-height:115%; font-size:11pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">By Lenz&#39;s law, this emf opposes further current change, making it more and more difficult for the ac current to keep growing\/decaying. Hence, the inductor delays current change. After some time, usually on the order of milliseconds, the current finally levels off at a final peak value given by,<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:10pt; line-height:115%; font-size:11pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">V = IX<\/span><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:7.33pt;\"><sub>L&nbsp;<\/sub><\/span><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">&nbsp;&nbsp;<\/span><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">X<\/span><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:7.33pt;\"><sub>L<\/sub><\/span><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">= wL<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:10pt; line-height:115%; font-size:11pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">X<\/span><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:7.33pt;\"><sub>L&nbsp;<\/sub><\/span><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">is called the inductive reactance\/resistance,<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:10pt; line-height:115%; font-size:11pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">L is the inductance of the inductor,<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:10pt; line-height:115%; font-size:11pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">I is the peak final\/steady current.<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:10pt; line-height:115%; font-size:11pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">&nbsp;<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:10pt; line-height:115%; font-size:11pt;\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">Eventually, the current lags voltage by 90&deg; in an inductor otherwise spoken, the voltage leads current by 90&deg; in the inductor circuit.&nbsp;<\/span><\/strong><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">This implies that while the voltage across the inductor is highest, the current is minimum and vice versa.<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:10pt; line-height:115%; font-size:11pt;\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">Example<\/span><\/strong><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:10pt; line-height:115%; font-size:11pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">Determine the inductive reactance when a 30.0mH inductor with negligible resistance is connected to a 1.3 KHz oscillator<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:10pt; line-height:115%; font-size:11pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">A. 39.0\u2126, B. 122.5\u2126, C. 245.0\u2126, D. 39K\u2126<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:10pt; line-height:115%; font-size:11pt;\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">C (2009\/2010, no13).<\/span><\/strong><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:10pt; line-height:115%; font-size:11pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">X<\/span><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:7.33pt;\"><sub>L<\/sub><\/span><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">&nbsp;= 2<\/span><img src=\"data:image\/png;base64,iVBORw0KGgoAAAANSUhEUgAAAAkAAAATCAYAAABC3CftAAAAAXNSR0IArs4c6QAAAARnQU1BAACxjwv8YQUAAAAJcEhZcwAADsMAAA7DAcdvqGQAAADJSURBVChT5Y4hCoRAGIWnGGWuYPAM3kCYbLaIJ9BgMpk9gocwickmRsULWAyewKDik3nLLrssC5u27AfDvHl8\/88IfMEfSPu+o2kalGX5dsZxvEmWZSEIAjiOgzRNEYYhTNNk7roO4jgObiqKAnme6xnEcYwoipg1jz\/5vo9hGJillJimiVlD6TxPCCGwritLwzB436E0zzNs22axLAsHnuEryzJ4nseirmtKbdui73t2lFzXRVVVLLZtg1IKSZLwrXnd+4GfSsAF5D5tJQWd5cQAAAAASUVORK5CYII=\" width=\"9\" height=\"19\" alt=\"\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">fL<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:10pt; line-height:115%; font-size:11pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">Inductive reactance (X<\/span><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:7.33pt;\"><sub>L<\/sub><\/span><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">) = ?, Reactance (L) = 30mH = 30 x 10<\/span><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:7.33pt;\"><sup>-3<\/sup><\/span><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">, f = 1.3 KHz = 13000Hz<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:10pt; line-height:115%; font-size:11pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">X<\/span><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:7.33pt;\"><sub>L<\/sub><\/span><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">&nbsp;= 2<\/span><img src=\"data:image\/png;base64,iVBORw0KGgoAAAANSUhEUgAAAAkAAAATCAYAAABC3CftAAAAAXNSR0IArs4c6QAAAARnQU1BAACxjwv8YQUAAAAJcEhZcwAADsMAAA7DAcdvqGQAAADJSURBVChT5Y4hCoRAGIWnGGWuYPAM3kCYbLaIJ9BgMpk9gocwickmRsULWAyewKDik3nLLrssC5u27AfDvHl8\/88IfMEfSPu+o2kalGX5dsZxvEmWZSEIAjiOgzRNEYYhTNNk7roO4jgObiqKAnme6xnEcYwoipg1jz\/5vo9hGJillJimiVlD6TxPCCGwritLwzB436E0zzNs22axLAsHnuEryzJ4nseirmtKbdui73t2lFzXRVVVLLZtg1IKSZLwrXnd+4GfSsAF5D5tJQWd5cQAAAAASUVORK5CYII=\" width=\"9\" height=\"19\" alt=\"\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">&nbsp;x 30 x 10<\/span><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:7.33pt;\"><sup>-3<\/sup><\/span><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:7.33pt;\"><sub>&nbsp;<\/sub><\/span><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">x 13000 = 245<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:10pt; text-align:justify; line-height:115%; font-size:11pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">X<\/span><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:7.33pt;\"><sub>L<\/sub><\/span><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">&nbsp;= 245\u2126<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:10pt; line-height:115%; font-size:11pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">&nbsp;<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:10pt; line-height:115%; font-size:11pt;\"><a name=\"_i3mc2v65nx3m\"><\/a><strong><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">Capacitor<\/span><\/strong><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:10pt; line-height:115%; font-size:11pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">The capacitor opposes voltage change in AC circuit. As more and more charge is deposited on the capacitor plates, it becomes increasingly difficult to keep adding more charge on the plates.&nbsp;<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:10pt; line-height:115%; font-size:11pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">Hence, voltage change is delayed until the voltage finally levels off at a final steady value. This final steady value of voltage, also called the peak value of voltage is given by,<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:10pt; line-height:115%; font-size:11pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">V = IX<\/span><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:7.33pt;\"><sub>C<\/sub><\/span><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:7.33pt;\"><sub>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<\/sub><\/span><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">&nbsp;<\/span><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">X<\/span><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:7.33pt;\"><sub>C<\/sub><\/span><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">= 1\/wC<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:10pt; line-height:115%; font-size:11pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">X<\/span><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:7.33pt;\"><sub>C&nbsp;<\/sub><\/span><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">is called the capacitive reactance\/resistance,<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:10pt; line-height:115%; font-size:11pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">C is the capacitance of the capacitor,<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:10pt; line-height:115%; font-size:11pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">w=2&pi;f.&nbsp;<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:10pt; line-height:115%; font-size:11pt;\"><a name=\"_wi5ahp44iean\"><\/a><em><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">PS: The relationship b\/w the peak voltage, current and reactance for each element can all be directly substituted for by the rms values. This means we can replace V and I simultaneously with V<\/span><\/em><em><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:7.33pt;\"><sub>rms&nbsp;<\/sub><\/span><\/em><em><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">and I<\/span><\/em><em><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:7.33pt;\"><sub>rms&nbsp;<\/sub><\/span><\/em><em><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">and the equations would remain valid.<\/span><\/em><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:10pt; line-height:115%; font-size:11pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">&nbsp;<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:10pt; line-height:115%; font-size:11pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">Q1: A computer is labeled 2.7A, 120V,60-Hz. Find (a) the average current (b) the average of the square of the current (c) the maximum current that this computer draws from a socket.<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:10pt; line-height:115%; font-size:11pt;\"><u><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">Solution<\/span><\/u><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:10pt; line-height:115%; font-size:11pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">Commercial electronics and devices are labelled with rms values of current and ac values of voltage. Power, if stated is the average power given by eqn (5) above.&nbsp;<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:10pt; line-height:115%; font-size:11pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">I<\/span><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:7.33pt;\"><sub>rms<\/sub><\/span><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">=2.7A<\/span><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<\/span><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">V<\/span><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:7.33pt;\"><sub>rms<\/sub><\/span><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">=120V<\/span><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<\/span><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">w=2&pi;&times;60=120&pi; rads<\/span><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:7.33pt;\"><sup>-1<\/sup><\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:10pt; line-height:115%; font-size:11pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">(a) ac current grows from 0 to max and back to 0. Hence, the average current over any whole number of cycles is clearly&nbsp;<\/span><u><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman'; color:#0000ff;\">zero<\/span><\/u><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:10pt; line-height:115%; font-size:11pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">(b) I<\/span><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:7.33pt;\"><sub>rms&nbsp;<\/sub><\/span><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">= &radic;(mean or average of the square of current).<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:10pt; line-height:115%; font-size:11pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<\/span><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">:. The average of the square of the current= I<\/span><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:7.33pt;\"><sup>2<\/sup><\/span><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:7.33pt;\"><sub>rms&nbsp;<\/sub><\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:10pt; line-height:115%; font-size:11pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<\/span><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">= 2.7<\/span><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:7.33pt;\"><sup>2&nbsp;<\/sup><\/span><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">=&nbsp;<\/span><u><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman'; color:#0000ff;\">7.3A<\/span><\/u><u><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:7.33pt; color:#0000ff;\"><sup>2<\/sup><\/span><\/u><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:10pt; line-height:115%; font-size:11pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">(c) The peak current I, is given by I=Irms&radic;2.<\/span><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:10pt; line-height:115%; font-size:11pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">:. I = 2.7&radic;2 =&nbsp;<\/span><u><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman'; color:#0000ff;\">3.8A (peak current)<\/span><\/u><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:10pt; line-height:115%; font-size:11pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">&nbsp;<\/span><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">Notice we didn&#39;t have any use for&nbsp;<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:10pt; line-height:115%; font-size:11pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">V<\/span><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:7.33pt;\"><sub>rms&nbsp;<\/sub><\/span><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">or w.&nbsp;<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:10pt; line-height:115%; font-size:11pt;\"><em><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">Sometimes, extraneous data can be given in problems to test if you can identity what you need to solve a problem. Always make sure to understand a problem and discover the tools you need to solve any problem. Understanding a problem is half-way through the problem.<\/span><\/em><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:10pt; line-height:115%; font-size:11pt;\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">&nbsp;<\/span><\/strong><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:10pt; line-height:115%; font-size:11pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">Q2: A pure inductor coil can draw 10A current from a 230V, 50Hz source. Find (i) the inductive reactance (ii) inductance of the coil (iii) write down the equations for voltage and current through the inductor at any instant.<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:10pt; line-height:115%; font-size:11pt;\"><u><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">Solution<\/span><\/u><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:10pt; line-height:115%; font-size:11pt;\"><em><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">We earlier remarked that ac commercial values are given in terms of rms values.&nbsp;<\/span><\/em><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">Both the voltage and current stated above are rms values.<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:10pt; line-height:115%; font-size:11pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">(i) V<\/span><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:7.33pt;\"><sub>rms<\/sub><\/span><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">=I<\/span><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:7.33pt;\"><sub>rms<\/sub><\/span><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">X<\/span><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:7.33pt;\"><sub>L&nbsp;<\/sub><\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:10pt; line-height:115%; font-size:11pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<\/span><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">:.<\/span><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">&nbsp;&nbsp;<\/span><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">X<\/span><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:7.33pt;\"><sub>L<\/sub><\/span><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">= (V\/I)<\/span><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:7.33pt;\"><sub>rms&nbsp;<\/sub><\/span><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">= 230\/10=&nbsp;<\/span><u><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman'; color:#0000ff;\">23 ohms<\/span><\/u><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:10pt; line-height:115%; font-size:11pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">(ii) X<\/span><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:7.33pt;\"><sub>L<\/sub><\/span><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">= wL<\/span><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">&nbsp;&nbsp;<\/span><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">=&gt; L=X<\/span><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:7.33pt;\"><sub>L<\/sub><\/span><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">\/w&nbsp;<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:10pt; line-height:115%; font-size:11pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<\/span><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">w= 2&pi;f = 2&pi;&times;50<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:10pt; line-height:115%; font-size:11pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">&nbsp;&nbsp;<\/span><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">:. w=100&pi; rads<\/span><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:7.33pt;\"><sup>-1&nbsp;<\/sup><\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:10pt; line-height:115%; font-size:11pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:7.33pt;\"><sup>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<\/sup><\/span><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">:. L = 23\/100&pi; =&nbsp;<\/span><u><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman'; color:#0000ff;\">0.073H<\/span><\/u><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:10pt; line-height:115%; font-size:11pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">(iii) v=Vcos(wt+z)<\/span><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">&nbsp;&nbsp;<\/span><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">i=Icos(wt+z) V\/I(peak values).<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:10pt; line-height:115%; font-size:11pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<\/span><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">V=V<\/span><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:7.33pt;\"><sub>rms<\/sub><\/span><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">&radic;2 = 230&radic;2 = 325V<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:10pt; line-height:115%; font-size:11pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<\/span><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">I=I<\/span><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:7.33pt;\"><sub>rms<\/sub><\/span><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">&radic;2 = 10&radic;2 = 14A<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:10pt; line-height:115%; font-size:11pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">&nbsp;&nbsp;<\/span><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">:.&nbsp;<\/span><u><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman'; color:#0000ff;\">v = 325cos(100&pi;t)<\/span><\/u><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:10pt; line-height:115%; font-size:11pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<\/span><u><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman'; color:#0000ff;\">i = 14cos(100&pi;t - &pi;\/2)<\/span><\/u><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">&nbsp;since current lags voltage by &pi;\/2 rad.<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:10pt; line-height:115%; font-size:11pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">&nbsp;<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:10pt; line-height:115%; font-size:11pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">Q3: An electric hair dryer is rated at 1500W, 120V. Calculate (a) the resistance (b) the rms current (c)the maximum power consumed by the dryer.<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:10pt; line-height:115%; font-size:11pt;\"><u><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">Solution<\/span><\/u><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:10pt; line-height:115%; font-size:11pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">The second form of average power, eqn (5) above, is more convenient here. Also, because the hair dryer is just a pure load\/resistance, the term cosz is equal to 1 since z=0&deg; for a pure resistance.&nbsp;<\/span><strong><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">The current and voltage are in phase and so, the phase angle, z=0&deg;<\/span><\/strong><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:10pt; line-height:115%; font-size:11pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">(a) P<\/span><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:7.33pt;\"><sub>avg<\/sub><\/span><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">= V<\/span><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:7.33pt;\"><sub>rms<\/sub><\/span><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">I<\/span><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:7.33pt;\"><sub>rms&nbsp;<\/sub><\/span><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">= V<\/span><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:7.33pt;\"><sup>2<\/sup><\/span><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:7.33pt;\"><sub>rms<\/sub><\/span><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">\/R :. R=V<\/span><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:7.33pt;\"><sup>2<\/sup><\/span><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:7.33pt;\"><sub>rms<\/sub><\/span><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">\/P<\/span><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:7.33pt;\"><sub>avg<\/sub><\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:10pt; line-height:115%; font-size:11pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">R = 120<\/span><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:7.33pt;\"><sup>2<\/sup><\/span><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">\/1500 =&nbsp;<\/span><u><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman'; color:#0000ff;\">9.6 ohms<\/span><\/u><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:10pt; line-height:115%; font-size:11pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">(b) I<\/span><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:7.33pt;\"><sub>rms<\/sub><\/span><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">=V<\/span><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:7.33pt;\"><sub>rms<\/sub><\/span><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">\/R = 120\/9.6 =&nbsp;<\/span><u><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman'; color:#0000ff;\">12.5A<\/span><\/u><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:10pt; line-height:115%; font-size:11pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">(c) P<\/span><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:7.33pt;\"><sub>max&nbsp;<\/sub><\/span><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">= VI where V\/I are the peak\/maximum values of voltage\/current.<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:10pt; line-height:115%; font-size:11pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<\/span><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">V=V<\/span><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:7.33pt;\"><sub>rms<\/sub><\/span><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">&radic;2 = 120&radic;2 = 169.7V, I=I<\/span><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:7.33pt;\"><sub>rms<\/sub><\/span><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">&radic;2 = 12.5&radic;2 = 17.7A<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:10pt; line-height:115%; font-size:11pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<\/span><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">:. P<\/span><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:7.33pt;\"><sub>max<\/sub><\/span><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">= 169.7&times;17.7 =&nbsp;<\/span><u><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman'; color:#0000ff;\">3000W<\/span><\/u><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:10pt; line-height:115%; font-size:11pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman'; color:#0000ff;\">&nbsp;<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:10pt; line-height:115%; font-size:11pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">Q4: A 318uf capacitor is connected across a 230V, 50Hz system. Determine (i) the capacitive reactance (ii) rms value of current. (iii) peak value of current<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:10pt; line-height:115%; font-size:11pt;\"><u><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">Solution<\/span><\/u><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:10pt; line-height:115%; font-size:11pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">w=2&pi;&times;50 = 100&pi; rads<\/span><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:7.33pt;\"><sup>-1&nbsp;<\/sup><\/span><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">C=318&times;10<\/span><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:7.33pt;\"><sup>-6<\/sup><\/span><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">F<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:10pt; line-height:115%; font-size:11pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">(i) :. X<\/span><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:7.33pt;\"><sub>C<\/sub><\/span><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">&nbsp;= 1\/wC = 1\/(100&pi;&times;318&times;10<\/span><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:7.33pt;\"><sup>-6<\/sup><\/span><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">)<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:10pt; line-height:115%; font-size:11pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<\/span><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">=&gt; X<\/span><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:7.33pt;\"><sub>C<\/sub><\/span><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">&nbsp;=&nbsp;<\/span><u><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman'; color:#0000ff;\">10 ohms<\/span><\/u><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:10pt; line-height:115%; font-size:11pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman'; color:#0000ff;\">&nbsp;<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:10pt; line-height:115%; font-size:11pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">(ii) I<\/span><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:7.33pt;\"><sub>rms<\/sub><\/span><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">= V<\/span><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:7.33pt;\"><sub>rms<\/sub><\/span><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">\/X<\/span><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:7.33pt;\"><sub>C<\/sub><\/span><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">&nbsp;= 230\/10<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:10pt; line-height:115%; font-size:11pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<\/span><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">:. I<\/span><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:7.33pt;\"><sub>rms<\/sub><\/span><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">&nbsp;=&nbsp;<\/span><u><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman'; color:#0000ff;\">23A<\/span><\/u><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:10pt; line-height:115%; font-size:11pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">(iii) I=I<\/span><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:7.33pt;\"><sub>rms<\/sub><\/span><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">\/&radic;2<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:10pt; line-height:115%; font-size:11pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<\/span><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">=&gt; I = 23\/&radic;2 =&nbsp;<\/span><u><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman'; color:#0000ff;\">16A<\/span><\/u><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:10pt; line-height:115%; font-size:11pt;\"><em><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">NB: Our final result doesn&#39;t mean the ac current is 16A. It only means that the current peaks at a maximum of 16A while it changes back and forth throughout the cycles. The current rises from 0A to a maximum of 16A during each cycle before it reverses and starts increasing in the opposite direction.<\/span><\/em><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:10pt; line-height:115%; font-size:11pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">&nbsp;<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:10pt; line-height:115%; font-size:11pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">Q5: The current across a 2.2 kilo ohm resistor is given by i = 5sin(2&pi;&times;100t + 45&deg;)mA. Find (i) the expression for the voltage through the resistor. (ii) the rms value of the voltage. (iii) what is the value of current through the load at t=0.4ms.<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:10pt; line-height:115%; font-size:11pt;\"><u><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">Solution<\/span><\/u><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:10pt; line-height:115%; font-size:11pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">I=5mA, w=100Hz, z=45&deg;, R=2.2kohms<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:10pt; line-height:115%; font-size:11pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">&nbsp;<\/span><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">V=IR<\/span><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">&nbsp;&nbsp;<\/span><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">=&gt;V=5&times;10<\/span><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:7.33pt;\"><sup>-3<\/sup><\/span><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">&times;2.2&times;10<\/span><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:7.33pt;\"><sup>3<\/sup><\/span><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">&nbsp;= 11V<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:10pt; line-height:115%; font-size:11pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">(i) v = Vsin(wt+z)<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:10pt; line-height:115%; font-size:11pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">&nbsp;&nbsp;<\/span><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">:. v =&nbsp;<\/span><u><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman'; color:#0000ff;\">11sin(200&pi;t + &pi;\/4)V<\/span><\/u><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:10pt; line-height:115%; font-size:11pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">(ii) V<\/span><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:7.33pt;\"><sub>rms<\/sub><\/span><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">=V\/&radic;2&nbsp;<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:10pt; line-height:115%; font-size:11pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<\/span><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">:. V<\/span><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:7.33pt;\"><sub>rms<\/sub><\/span><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">=11<\/span><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">\/&radic;2 =&gt; V<\/span><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:7.33pt;\"><sub>rms<\/sub><\/span><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">&nbsp;=&nbsp;<\/span><u><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman'; color:#0000ff;\">7.78V<\/span><\/u><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:10pt; line-height:115%; font-size:11pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">(iii) at t=0.4ms, i=5sin(200&pi;&times;0.4 + &pi;\/4)<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:10pt; line-height:115%; font-size:11pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<\/span><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">=&gt; i = 5sin(629rad)<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:10pt; line-height:115%; font-size:11pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<\/span><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">:. i =&nbsp;<\/span><u><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman'; color:#0000ff;\">-0.707A<\/span><\/u><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:10pt; line-height:115%; font-size:11pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">&nbsp;<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:10pt; line-height:115%; font-size:11pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">&nbsp;<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:10pt; line-height:115%; font-size:11pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">&nbsp;<\/span><\/p>\r\n\r\n<\/body>\r\n\r\n<\/html>",
  "chapIndex": "AC CIRCUIT"
}